A11y-toggle is a small script to build accessible content toggles and disclosure
widgets. It focuses on making show/hide interactions usable for keyboard and
assistive technology users while staying close to plain HTML and CSS.

{% callout %}
For a React version of a11y-toggle, check [react-a11y-disclosure](https://github.com/KittyGiraudel/react-a11y-disclosure)
which implements the same pattern with a lightweight hook.
{% endcallout %}

## What it does

- **State management**: wires up buttons and controlled regions so that the
  open / closed state is always in sync between the DOM and what assistive
  technologies expose.
- **ARIA attributes**: handles the boring but important details like
  `aria-expanded`, `aria-controls` and relationships between toggles and the
  content they reveal.
- **Progressive enhancement**: starts from semantic markup and only adds the
  JavaScript needed to toggle visibility and state.

You keep full control over the HTML and styling; a11y-toggle takes care of the
accessibility contract that is easy to overlook.

## Where it fits

a11y-toggle is useful for FAQs, disclosure sections, filter panels, settings
panels and any place where content is conditionally revealed. It is deliberately
minimal so it can be dropped into existing projects without imposing a design
system or component framework.

The project lives on GitHub, where you can find installation instructions,
examples and tips for integrating it into different codebases.

